07768nam a22012615i 9783110295290DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20132013gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2012047967  a(OCoLC)853251526  a97831102952907 a10.1515/97831102952902doi  a(DE-B1597)178525  a(OCoLC)851970203  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP37.5.C74bC74 2013 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aCreativity and the Agile Mind :bA Multi-Disciplinary Study of a Multi-Faceted Phenomenon /ced. by Tony Veale, Kurt Feyaerts, Charles Forceville. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (380 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aApplications of Cognitive Linguistics [ACL] ,x1861-4078 ;v210 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCreativity is a highly-prized quality in any modern endeavor, whether artistic, scientific or professional. Though a much-studied subject, and the topic of a great many case-studies, the field of creativity research is still very much an open one. Creativity remains a field where absolute definitions hold very little water, and where true insight can only emerge when we properly appreciate - from a nuanced, multi-disciplinary perspective - the crucial distinction between the producer's perspective and the consumer's perspective. Theories that afford us a critical appreciation of a creative work do not similarly afford a explanatory insight into the origins and development of the work. As researchers, we must approach creativity both as producers - to consider the vast search-spaces that a producer encounters, and to appreciate the need for heuristic strategies for negotiating this space - and as consumers, to appreciate the levels of shared knowledge (foreground and background) that is exploited by the producer to achieve a knowingly creative effect in the mind of the consumer. This volume thus brings together both producers and consumers in a cross-disciplinary exploration of this complex, many-faceted phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCognitive grammar. 0aCreativity (Linguistics) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxCoordinate constructions. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aKreativität. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive Science.  aCreativity.  aLanguage.  aMusic.  aVisual Communication.1 aBrône, Geert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgers, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCancino, Juan Parra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCienki, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoessens, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaelemans, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Bleser, Frederik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Smedt, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeyaerts, Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeyaerts, Kurt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aForceville, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForceville, Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHanks, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHao, Yanfen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIndurkhya, Bipin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanglotz, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeesters, Gert,